Consumer complaint narrative: Despite multiple attempts, I have been unable to resolve the issue of fraudulent inquiries appearing on my consumer report. These inquiries are not associated with me in any way, and I bear no responsibility for them. Their presence has caused significant mental and financial distress. As a victim of identity theft, I have no alternative but to consider legal action if this matter is not appropriately addressed. These inaccurate and fraudulent items on my consumer report have hindered my ability to purchase my dream house and provide for my family 's needs. The impact on my financial well-being has been substantial. For your reference, I have attached a copy of the letter I previously sent to the Federal Trade Commission ( FTC ), which outlines this issue and seeks resolution.

XXXX, Experian, as well as XXXX are all consumer reporting agencies and I am the consumer. According to 15 USC 6801, I have the right to make sure my private information isn't shared, and it states " It is the policy of the Congress that each financial institution has an affirmative and continuing obligation to respect the privacy of its customers and to protect the security and confidentiality of those customer 's nonpublic personal information. '' Furnisher of Information to Credit Agencies is defined as " the financial institution and the consumer reporting agencies. By definition, Furnisher of Information to Credit Agencies is a financial institution under that same title. Now, 15 USC 1681 section 604 a section 2 states, " In general subject to subsection ( c ), any consumer reporting agency may furnish a consumer report under the following circumstances and no other : in accordance with the written instruction of the consumer to whom it relates. '' Furnisher of Information to Credit Agencies, the financial institution and credit reporting agencies XXXX, Experian and XXXX, do not have my consent to furnish this information ; whether that be written, nonwritten, verbal, nonverbal, or implied, they do not have my consent. Any and all consent is revoked. Also, I was never informed of my right to exercise my nondisclosure option. 15 USC 6802 ( b ) ( c ) states, " a financial institution may not disclose nonpublic personal information to a nonaffliated third party uness -- the consumer is given an explanation of how the consumer can exercise that nondisclosure option. '' In addition to that USC, one that corresponds with that here is USC 1681C ( a ) ( 5 ) which states the following : " Except as authorized under subsection ( b ), no consumer reporting agency may make any consumer report containing any of the following items of information : Any other adverse item of information, other than records of convictions of crimes which antedates the report by more than seven years. '' Several accounts fall under the category of adverse items which is against the law as they are reporting without my permission. 12 CFR 1016.7 states, " A consumer may exercise the right to opt out at any time. '' I am opting out of your reporting services. To back this up, 15 USC 1681e states, " Every consumer reporting agency shall maintain reasonable procedures designed to avoid violations of section 1681c of this title and to limit the furnishing of consumer reports to the purposes listed under section 1681b of this title. '' ; and 15 USC 1681s-2 ( A ) ( 1 ) states, " A personal shall not furnish any information relating to a consumer to any consumer reporting agency if the person knows or has a reasonable cause to believe that the information is inaccurate. XXXX, Experian, and XXXX are not maintaining reasonable procedures.
Company public response: Company has responded to the consumer and the CFPB and chooses not to provide a public response

Consumer complaint narrative: TO WHO MAY CONCERN, To addressed the issues within my complaint, I the consumer remains dissatisfied due to I have sent then a bank certified check to Moneylion XXXX  that I do not owe and believe to be fraudulent activity attached to my name. Consumer complaint narrative: According to the Fair Credit Reporting Act 15 USC 1681 section 602 a states " There is a need to insure that consumer reporting agencies exercise their grave responsibilities with fairness, impartiality, and a respect for the consumers right to privacy. '' XXXX and XXXX are consumer reporting agencies and I am the Consumer. I have the right to make sure my private information isn't shared which is backed by 15 USC 6801 which states '' It is the policy of the Congress that each financial institution has an affirmative and continuing obligation to respect the privacy of its customers and to protect the security and confidentiality of those customers nonpublic personal information. '' ( Furnisher of information to credit agencies ) is a financial institution by definition under that title. 15 USC 1681 section 604 a section 2 states that " In general Subject to subsection ( c ), any consumer reporting agency may furnish a consumer report under the following circumstances and no other : in accordance with the written instructions of the consumer to whom it relates. '' ( Furnisher of information to credit agencies ) the financial institution and the Consumer reporting agencies XXXX and XXXX do not have my consent to furnish this information and they surely do not have my written consent. Any and all consent to XXXX, XXXX, ( Furnisher of information to credit agencies ) whether it be verbal, non-verbal, written, implied or otherwise is revoked. 15 USC 6802 ( b ) ( c ) states that " A financial institution may not disclose nonpublic personal information to a nonaffiliated third party unless the consumer is given an explanation of how the consumer can exercise that nondisclosure option. '' ( Furnisher of information to credit agencies ) Never informed me of my right to exercise my nondisclosure option. Not only that 15 USC 1681C ( a ) ( 5 ) states '' Except as authorized under subsection ( b ), no consumer reporting agency may make any consumer report containing any of the following items of information Any other adverse item of information, other than records of convictions of crimes which antedates the report by more than seven years. '' This account is an adverse item they are reporting again without my permission which is against the law. 15 U.S. Code 1681s2 ( A ) ( 1 ) A states " A person shall not furnish any information relating to a consumer to any consumer reporting agency if the person knows or has reasonable cause to believe that the information is inaccurate. 15 U.S. Code 1681e states '' Every consumer reporting agency shall maintain reasonable procedures designed to avoid violations of section 1681c of this title and to limit the furnishing of consumer reports to the purposes listed under section 1681b of this title. XXXX and XXXX are not maintaining reasonable procedures. Also 12 CFR 1016.7 states that " A consumer may exercise the right to opt out at any time. '' I am opting out of your reporting services.

Consumer complaint narrative:
I XXXX XXXX XXXX, the federally protected consumer, has placed numerous complaints through the CFPB ( 15 u.s.Code 6805 and 16 CFR 131.1 ) and certified mail for the entire year of XXXX about XXXX XXXX and Experian Consumer Services willful non compliance of the Fair Credit Reporting Act and Privacy Act of 1974 by the sharing of inaccurate, non public, personal information on my consumer report. ( FCRA Sec 603 ( d ) ( 1 ) ) without my expressed written consent. ( FCRA Sec 604 ( a ) ( 2 ) ). XXXX XXXX and Experian Consumer Services is also currently past the 30 day allotment to resolve this ongoing dispute which is also documented via the complaint placed via the CFPB since the last complaint that has been placed, on XX/XX/XXXX and XX/XX/XXXX. 
The law states that it is illegal to have a consumer report containing information solely as to transactions or experiences between the consumer and the person making the report ( FCRA Sec 603 ( d ) ( 2 ) ( a ) ( i ). I've repeatedly stated the reasonable procedures that congress has set forth for meeting the needs of commerce for consumer credit, personnel, insurance, and other information in a manner which is fair and equitable to the consumer and the consumer reporting agencies, XXXX XXXX and Experian Consumer Services, has had no regards to the confidentiality, accuracy, relevancy, and proper utilization of such information in accordance with the requirements of the Fair Credit Reporting Act. XXXX XXXX and Experian Consumer Services has never provided their method and/or proof of verification that gives them the authority to report inaccurate, non-public, personal information on my consumer report. Which is documented via the CFPB with their responses that has not addressed the issue of their willful non-compliance of the Fair Credit Reporting Act and Privacy Act of 1974 by the sharing of inaccurate, non-public, personal information on my consumer report. 
There is also income being reported, by XXXX XXXX, on my consumer report as well ( XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX ) which also goes against federal regulations. Nor has this account been properly verified and/or validated according to federal guidelines. 
According to the compliance procedures of the fair credit reporting act every consumer reporting agency shall maintain reasonable procedures designed to avoid violations of section 605 [ 1681c ] and to limit the furnishing of consumer reports to the purposes listed under section 604 [ 1681b ] of this title. 

I have attached the following : Passport Card, CAF Notice, Power Of Attorney, Fee Schedule, consumer report ( s ), Opt Out Confirmation ( s )

Consumer complaint narrative:
This letter is to formally advise you that I believe your company has violated several of my consumer rights. Specifically, you failed to validate a debt at my request, which is a FDCPA violation and you continued to report a disputed debt to the Credit Bureaus : another FCRA violation. Not only have you ignored my prior requests for validation of debt but you continue to report this debt to the credit bureaus causing damage to my character. This letter will again request that you follow the FDCPA and please provide the following validation of debt request : -Proof of your right to own/collect this alleged debt -Balance claimed including all fees, interest and penalties -Contract bearing my personal signature As you may be aware, " Estoppel by Silence '' legally means that you had a duty to speak but failed to do so therefore, that must mean you agree with me that this debt is false. I will use the Estoppel in my defense. I expect to receive the proof requested above within 15 days of this letter. Should you again ignore my request for validation of debt I reserve the right to sue your company for violations of my consumer rig
hts as specified under both the FDCPA and the FCRA. I may also seek damages from you if warranted.

Consumer complaint narrative: I am writing to formally file a complaint against XXXX located in XXXX, GA ; XXXX located in XXXX, TX and TRANSUNION located in XXXX, PA. This company has repeatedly violated my consumer rights under the Fair Credit Reporting Act, causing me significant financial and mental distress. To begin with, they have reported an erroneous and unverifiable account on my credit report, and despite my requests for proof of claim, they have failed to provide the necessary documentation as required by the FCRA. Despite my persistent efforts to resolve this issue over the past several months, XXXX, XXXX AND TRANSUNION has consistently ignored my communications and legal submissions aimed at removing this inaccurate information from my credit report. It is disheartening to note that there are numerous other complaints lodged against this company for their illegal and unethical business practices, yet they continue to operate. The unprofessional and negligent behavior of this XXXX bureaus namely XXXX, XXXX AND TRANSUNION has inflicted severe harm not only on my ability to establish credit and secure favorable interest rates but also on my professional reputation and personal well-being. I implore you to assist not only me but also other consumers facing similar issues by putting an immediate stop to these unethical and immoral business practices. I genuinely appreciate your time and assistance in addressing this matter and eagerly await your response.

Consumer complaint narrative:
Consumer Financial Protection Bureau XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX Re : Complaint Against Reporting Entity for Violation of Fair Credit Reporting Act Dear Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, I am writing to file a formal complaint against TRANSUNION XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX ( hereinafter referred to as " TRANSUNION '' ) regarding their non-compliance with the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ) and, specifically, their failure to adhere to the provisions outlined in Section 611 ( a ) ( 8 ) of the FCRA. This complaint is submitted to the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau ( CFPB ) for investigation and appropriate action. 

On XX/XX/XXXX, I, as a credit consultant, sent a certified letter to On XX/XX/XXXX, I, as a credit consultant, sent a certified letter to TRANSUNION requesting the validation of a collection account as per the provisions set forth in the FCRA. The collection account in question pertains to XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX  which alleges that I opened an account on XX/XX/XXXX, and currently maintains a balance of {$200.00}. The FCRA mandates that the credit bureau, in this case, TRANSUNION must ensure the accuracy and completeness of the information they report. 

We are filing this complaint on behalf of our client, who is experiencing issues with a closed account reporting negative information on their credit report. Pursuant to our efforts to address this matter, we sent a Validation of Debt letter to the reporting entity, as allowed under the FCRA. Despite our repeated attempts, we have not received any response from the reporting entity. 

This lack of cooperation is a clear violation of our client 's rights under the FCRA, particularly under the following sections : FCRA Section 611 ( a ) ( 1 ) ( A ) : This section requires consumer reporting agencies to promptly investigate disputes regarding the completeness or accuracy of any information provided by a consumer and to correct or remove any inaccurate information. 

FCRA Section 623 ( a ) ( 2 ) : This section mandates furnishers of information to report accurately and prohibits the reporting of information that they know or have reasonable cause to believe is inaccurate. 

Enclosed, please find a copy of the Validation of Debt letter we sent to the reporting entity, along with proof of delivery. We believe that our client 's rights have been willfully neglected, and we seek the intervention of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau to ensure a fair resolution in accordance with the FCRA. 

We kindly request that the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau conduct a thorough investigation into this matter, compelling the reporting entity to respond appropriately and take corrective action. We appreciate your prompt attention to this issue and look forward to a swift resolution. 

If you require any additional information or documentation, please do not hesitate to contact me at XXXX Thank you for your commitment to protecting consumers ' rights and ensuring the fair implementation of the FCRA. 

Sincerely, XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX

Consumer complaint narrative:
XXXX XXXX Trans Union Re : Dispute of Inaccurate Late Payment Entry - 15 U.S. Code 1681a Dear Sir/Madam, I am writing to dispute a late payment entry on my credit report, which I believe is inaccurate and should be removed and updated to paid as agreed, never late in accordance with the Fair Credit Reporting Act ( FCRA ), specifically 15 U.S. Code 1681a. This late payment entry is adversely affecting my credit profile, and I am seeking its correction as mandated by federal law. 

Below are the details of the disputed late payment : Creditor Name : Trans Union Date of Late Payment : XX/XX/XXXX Amount of Late Payment : XXXX I contend that this late payment entry is erroneous for the following reasons : Incorrect Reporting : The late payment reported on XX/XX/XXXX for with [ XXXX XXXX XXXX ] is factually incorrect. According to my records, I made a timely payment for this account, and there should not be any late payment recorded. This discrepancy goes against the FCRA, which obligates credit reporting agencies to ensure the accuracy of information. 
Supporting Documentation : To substantiate my dispute, I have enclosed copies of relevant documentation, including bank statements and payment receipts, which clearly demonstrate that I made the payment on time. These documents should serve as compelling evidence that the reported late payment is inaccurate. 
I kindly request that you investigate this matter promptly in accordance with the FCRA 's provisions, including 15 U.S. Code 1681i. Please correct any inaccuracies found during your investigation and provide me with a revised copy of my credit report once these corrections have been made. I emphasize the importance of a swift resolution, given the potential adverse impact on my creditworthiness. 

Enclosed Copies of payment receipts for with [ XXXX XXXX ] I anticipate your prompt attention to this matter and adherence to the federal laws governing credit reporting. 

Thank you for your assistance in resolving this dispute promptly and accurately. 

Sincerely, XXXX XXXX Please ensure you enclose the necessary documents and modify the letter to include any specific details relevant to your situation before sending it to the credit bureau.

Product: Checking or savings account
Consumer complaint narrative:
On XX/XX/2024 I opened a checking/money market account with Truist with XXXX Check in the amount of {$60000.00} from XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX I received a letter that the account had been closed with no explanation and that I needed to deposit funds to make the account whole and to not withdraw or present any payments against it. 

On XX/XX/XXXX, I went to the bank and spoke with Branch Manager/Assistant VP ; XXXX XXXX in regards and after making a phone call she was instructed that I needed to provide a bank statement from XXXXXXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX showing the funds were removed from my account. At that moment, I went across the street, got a copy from XXXX XXXX XXXX, and provided it to XXXX XXXX, and she scanned and emailed to her fraud team. She advised the funds are available and the money cleared so there shouldn't be any further issues. 

As of today, after daily calls and holding for over an hour each time to speak with someone who can help me, I still have not received any calls from them and they have not released my funds even though it has cleared.
Company public response: Company has responded to the consumer and the CFPB and chooses not to provide a public response

Consumer complaint narrative:
I hope this letter finds you well. I am writing to bring to your attention a discrepancy in my credit report maintained by your bureau. Upon reviewing my credit history, I have noticed the presence of inaccurate late payments, which do not accurately reflect my payment history. 
I pride myself on being a responsible and diligent payer, consistently meeting my financial obligations on time. The reported late payments are inconsistent with my financial behavior, and I believe there has been an error in the reporting process. 
Account Information : XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXXXXXX Those payments were made on time. I am requesting that the late payment markings be updated to reflect my accurate payment history. 

XXXX XXXX XXXX XXXX Those payments were made on time. I am requesting that the late payment markings be updated to reflect my accurate payment history. 

I am kindly requesting a thorough investigation into this matter and the prompt correction of the inaccurate information on my credit report. I understand the importance of accurate credit reporting and the impact it has on my overall financial well-being. 
As such, I request your cooperation in rectifying this error as soon as possible.

Consumer complaint narrative:
This letter is to formally advise you that I believe your company has violated several of my consumer rights. Specifically, you failed to validate a debt at my request, which is a FDCPA violation and you continued to report a disputed debt to the Credit Bureaus : another FCRA violation. Not only have you ignored my prior requests for validation of debt but you continue to report this debt to the credit bureaus causing damage to my character. This letter will again request that you follow the FDCPA and please provide the following validation of debt request : -Proof of your right to own/collect this alleged debt -Balance claimed including all fees, interest and penalties -Contract bearing my personal signature As you may be aware, " Estoppel by Silence '' legally means that you had a duty to speak but failed to do so therefore, that must mean you agree with me that this debt is false. I will use the Estoppel in my defense. I expect to receive the proof requested above within 15 days of this letter.

Should you again ignore my request for validation of debt I reserve the right to sue your company for violations of my consumer rights as specified under both the FDCPA and the FCRA. I may also seek damages from you if warranted.

Consumer complaint narrative:
I hope this letter finds you well. I am writing to express my dissatisfaction and frustration regarding the numerous unsuccessful attempts to address and rectify the presence of a charge-off and late closed accounts on my credit report. Despite multiple efforts to dispute and correct this information, I have yet to see a resolution, and I am compelled to bring this matter to your attention. 

I have made numerous attempts to dispute the presence of a charge-off and late closed accounts on my credit report through the designated dispute channels, yet these efforts have yielded no positive results. The persistence of these inaccurate and damaging entries has significantly affected my creditworthiness, causing considerable hardship in various financial matters. 

I am deeply concerned about the impact of these inaccuracies on my ability to secure favorable terms for credit, loans, and other financial services. I believe it is essential to rectify these errors promptly to ensure the accuracy of my credit report and, by extension, my financial standing. 

I am submitting this formal complaint to request a thorough and immediate investigation into the charge-off and late closed accounts listed on my credit report. I insist on a comprehensive review of the evidence provided in my previous disputes, and I urge you to take the necessary steps to remove these inaccuracies promptly. 

Enclosed with this letter, you will find copies of my previous dispute letters, supporting documentation, and any relevant correspondence for your reference. I am asking for your assistance to remove the accounts in my credit file : XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$0.00} - I see things may be inaccurate. Start looking at the account name, opening date, and high balance. I believe this information may be inaccurate. Immediate removal of this item is necessary. 

XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$0.00} - I see things may be inaccurate. Start looking at the account name, opening date, and account status. I believe this information may be inaccurate. I need this deleted now. 

XXXX XXXX XXXXXXXX Balance Owed : {$750.00} - Investigate the way this account is reporting the date of last activity, account name, and opening date. I believe this information may be inaccurate. I need this removed now. 

XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$0.00} - Investigate the way this account is reporting the date of last activity, account name, and opening date. I believe this information may be inaccurate. I need this removed now. 

XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$140.00} - I requested an investigation and the removal of the charge-off status. No changes were made. No investigation was conducted at all. You had optimal time to review this matter and make the appropriate corrections, you elected not to. Please remove this item immediately. 

XXXX XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$400.00} - I believe this account is reporting inaccurately. I do not recall ever having a legal obligation with this company nor do I believe one exists. Please provide me verifiable proof this account belongs to me. I request a signed contract which is the ONLY LEGAL authority that stipulates an agreement. Please remove it. 

XXXX XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$470.00} - The payment history and status is inaccurate. According to FCRA 's Compliance/Obsolescence date determines when the 7-year reporting period begins for accounts that have been charged-off. Please delete this account immediately. 

XXXX XXXX Balance Owed : {$0.00} - You are reporting inaccurate information for this particular account. Remove the balance indicated, change it to zero and delete this account promptly. 
XXXX XXXX XXXXXXXX Balance Owed : {$1400.00} - The limit to this account was a fraction of the amount due it was stating. That is utterly unfathomable! Had a proper investigation been conducted you would have seen the error and corrected it immediately. You failed to do your job ; you must now REMOVE THIS ITEM ALTOGETHER.

Consumer complaint narrative:
There are multiple instances of noncompliance with mandated reporting criteria, thus the information in my report isn't accurate and comprehensive! Having said that, I refute your claims and challenge you to show me that you have the authority to publish this inaccurate, misleading information to my credit report.

15 U.S.C. Section 1681e states that " a consumer reporting agency shall follow reasonable procedures to assure maximum possible accuracy of the information concerning the individual about whom the report relates whenever it prepares a consumer report. '' According to 12 CFR Part 1022 ( Regulation V ) requires furnishers to : Furnish information concerning accounts or other relationships with a consumer that has integrity.

Furnish information about accounts or other relationships with a consumer that is accurate.

C - Conduct reasonable investigations of consumer disputes According to CRRG, in order to make a lawful report, you must follow the Metro 2 compliance standards.

Also as stated in the CRRG Any Deviation From These Standards Jeopardizes The Integrity of The Data. This means that any mistakes in reporting claims can make the information less accurate and it affects the accuracy of any federally regulated reports.

Therefore, I am invoking my rights to challenge these inaccurate and non-compliant items. Neglecting my demand will only prove that you DO NOT care about my rights as a consumer. Its NOT FAIR for you to report information that isnt confirmed to be ethical and meets the standards of certified reporting. Again, I am challenging these claims and asking for proof of the proper reporting standards.

You are violating my rights! I have listed the concerns about your reporting in this document. It's not complete and does not meet my standards according to law, you must certify all aspects of required FCRA/ Metro 2 compliance which is done truthfully, correctly ( in a timely manner ), completely AND accurately as well - or else I would have to escalate these issues to the CFPB , FTC and my Attorney General.
